    cellular: "Exposure therapy is the most effective treatment for anxiety disorders and specific phobias. It involves systematic confrontation with feared stimuli while preventing avoidance or safety behaviors. Mechanisms include habituation (anxiety naturally decreases with prolonged exposure), inhibitory learning (new safety associations compete with fear associations), and self-efficacy (building confidence through successful confrontation). Types: in vivo (real-life), imaginal (mental imagery), interoceptive (body sensations), and virtual reality. Exposure hierarchies rank feared situations from least to most anxiety-provoking. The therapist guides gradual progression up the hierarchy. Response prevention is essential: safety behaviors must be eliminated during exposure.",
