    cellular: "Eye Movement Desensitization and Reprocessing (EMDR) is an evidence-based treatment for PTSD that uses bilateral stimulation (eye movements, tapping, or auditory tones) during trauma memory processing. Francine Shapiro developed EMDR based on the Adaptive Information Processing (AIP) model, which posits that traumatic memories are inadequately processed and stored with the original distressing emotions. EMDR has 8 phases: history/treatment planning, preparation (stabilization and resource installation), assessment (identifying target memory components), desensitization (bilateral stimulation while holding the memory), installation (strengthening positive cognition), body scan (checking for residual tension), closure (returning to equilibrium), and reevaluation (reviewing progress). EMDR is recommended as a first-line trauma treatment by the WHO and VA/DoD.",
