    title: "Person-Centered Therapy",
    cellular: "Carl Rogers developed person-centered therapy (PCT) based on the premise that individuals have an inherent tendency toward growth and self-actualization. Three core conditions are both necessary and sufficient for therapeutic change: unconditional positive regard (acceptance without judgment), empathic understanding (deeply understanding the client's frame of reference), and congruence (therapist genuineness and authenticity). The therapist creates a facilitative environment rather than directing change. Conditions of worth (learning that love is conditional on certain behaviors) create incongruence between the self-concept and experience. PCT is non-directive: the therapist follows the client's lead. Research consistently shows the therapeutic relationship is the strongest predictor of outcome across all therapy modalities.",
